How to Buy a House as a Data Scientist

Predicting heating costs with the 2015 Residential Energy Consumption Survey

Avriana Allen | March 15, 2020

The Data

The 2015 Residential Energy Consumption Survey, (the RECS), was created from a housing survey randomly assigned to over 5 thousand households combined with energy consumption and billing data from their energy suppliers. With broad and specific questions, the survey tallies everything from the number of occupants to the number of swamp coolers for any given household.

Looking at all the data, I wondered, would it be possible to predict heating costs or energy use for a household accurately? If so, what would the predictors be?

After removing the imputation flags, and hand selecting 132 possible predictors, I split the data into four pieces. 70 percent was set aside for model building while the remaining 30 percent was split three ways: exploration, selection and performance.

Selecting a predictor

The first question I asked was what to predict? There were two potential candidates, the total amount of money spent on heating, or the total amount of energy spend on heating. To decide between the two options, I selected all the non-categorical variables, 39 not counting my two potential candidates and considered the correlations.

Any correlation under 0.5 was dropped, leaving me leaning toward predicting the amount of energy spent on heating. It had more variables so I thought it would be more interesting to work with.

The pairwise plots confirmed my thoughts. I would predict the amount of energy spent on heating.

Reducing the predictors

Moving into model building, I knew I had set of continuous predictors. However, I still had close to 90 categorical variables. I decided to use a lasso to reduce this number.

Using a formula containing all the categorical variables, I used cross-fold validation to keep only the variables that the lasso deemed important, reducing the number of variables I intended to use from 90 to 54.

Formulas and Functions

My initial look at the correlations between variables and the total amount of energy spent on heating suggested that there might be a strong linear correlation. I decided to begin by trying a linear model with three different formulas.

The first contained only the variables that were categorical, the second all the variables that were continuous, and the final model contained all the variables.

Fitting a Linear Model

Given the number of variables, I decided to use 5 folds instead of 10 for fitting my linear models. After creating a data set with these folds, the formulas and the respective fits, I averaged the R and R-squared tests to see how much of the variance was explained.

Linear Model Comparisons
form_name r_squared adj_r_squared
all 0.9774030 0.9758090
cont 0.9532564 0.9530944
fact 0.6702420 0.6482799

Obviously, the model with all the selected variables does the best, though the categorical variable come in a close second. The residuals are fairly evenly distributed for both models although the populations has heavier tails than we might hope.

Fitting a Lasso

The best linear model contains a high number of variables. I wanted to know if all of the variables were needed, so I ran a lasso using the formula with all of the preselected variables. To do this, I split the data into two pieces, a training set of about 75 percent of the data and a test set of the remaining 25 percent.

On the training data, I used a 10-fold cross-validated lasso to choose my lambada. I created a new data set that contained the lasso fits and used it to calculate the MSE, MSE squared and amount of variance explained.

Lasso Model Comparisons
method test_mse explained
lasso_min 32599395 0.9714315
lasso_1se 132389834 0.8839802

The lasso does better than two of the linear models but doesnt quite beat out our top linear model.

Subsets and Random Forests

Although sub-setting the data would have been ideal, the collinearity between variables prevented me from using that method, I decide to try a Random Forest Model instead.

Although it was simple to apply, and fit the data quite well, I lacked the understanding to know exactly what it was doing, though I understood the concept behind it.

Models to Pass

Based upon the different models I have tried, I decided to pass three models to compete in selection. They are the top two linear models and the lasso.

Model Selection

To compare the three models, I created two data sets; one for lasso and the other for the two linear models. I compared the lassos amount of explained variance and the R and R-Squared tests to see which model did best on this untouched data.

Linear Models
form_name r_squared adj_r_squared

Lasso Models

Each model performs quite well, so I decided to graph the predicted values from each model against the true values and see I could gain any insight.

I decided that the lasso would be my final model because it performed at the same level as the linear model, but, at least in theory, reduced the number of variables in use.

Final Model

Unpacking the final data, I created a new data set that contained the lasso and selected the lambada, before fitting it to the performance set and calculating the amount of explained variance.

Final Model Fit
method test_mse explained
lasso_min 27025709 0.9788629
lasso_1se 118441058 0.9073660

Looking at the predictions verses the actual data, we can see that the model does a great job of predicting the data.

Finally, I fit the model to all of the data and graphed the residuals.

Final Model Fit with all the data
test_mse explained
27023323 0.9788648

Final Thoughts

If I were to restart this project knowing what I know now, I would have changed my approach. Instead of selecting variables related to heating, I would have selected variables of easily quantifiable things. Although some of the final predictors are practical, like insulation, or number of children, others are a little less helpful.

It also would have been interesting to explore the variables more closely. Because I had so many, I didnt get very close to many so it would have been interesting to see the relationships between variables on a localized level.

I also would explore non-linear models. My model fitting was set up to be linear from the moment I decided to use correlation. It does a very good job of explaining the data but I would be interested to see if there were other models that fit as well.
